			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(center)">TO THE PUBLIC</p>
				<p rend="align(center)">THE OCCIDENT&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">The oldest Jewish periodical in the English language&#44; has finished its<lb/> <hi rend="italics">twenty&#45;fifth</hi> volume.  Under the able editorship of the late <persName>Rev. Isaac<lb/> Leeser</persName>&#44; it has become a renowned champion of Judaism&#44; and a successful<lb/> promoter of Jewish literature.  It was his earnest wish that its publication<lb/> should be continued after his death.  Personally&#44; and in his will&#44; he requested<lb/> the subscriber to take editorial charge of it&#44; and although there were many<lb/> reasons to cause hesitancy in accepting the trust&#44; two circumstances over&#45;<lb/>came his reluctance.  The one was a natural anxiety that the desire of his<lb/> lamented friend should be fulfilled&#44; and the other&#44; a conviction that the Jews<lb/> of <placeName>America</placeName> still need an organ which has so long maintained its position.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Its literary character will be such as to make it attractive to all households&#44;<lb/> and neither pains nor expense will be spared to procure contributions on<lb/> Jewish subjects from persons of talent.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Its religious position is too well defined to need any explanation.  In the<lb/> words of <persName>Mr. Leeser</persName>&#44; &#8220;Whatever can promote the welfare of Israelites and<lb/> their faith&#44; shall always find an ardent advocate in it&#59; whatever is hostile to<lb/> either&#44; shall ever meet its decided opposition.&#8221;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">To Jewish families&#44; everywhere&#44; who desire to know the events which<lb/> affect their co&#45;religionists in all parts of the world&#44; this work will be a wel&#45;<lb/>come visitor.  Hebrew scholars will find its pages enriched with many arti&#45;<lb/>cles instructive even to the learned&#44; and the public generally will receive<lb/> from it information of a character elsewhere unattainable.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">The great and increasing importance of the numerous and influential order<lb/> of B&#39;nai Berith&#44; will be recognized&#44; by the creation of a B. B. department in<lb/> this magazine.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">It appears in monthly parts of at least forty&#45;eight pages octavo&#44; forming&#44;<lb/> at the end of the year&#44; a handsome volume.  The price is <hi rend="italics">Four</hi> Dollars per<lb/> annum&#44; in advance.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Advertisements will be inserted on the cover at the rate of 25 cents per<lb/> line&#44; for the first insertion&#59; every subsequent one will be charged 20 cents.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Annual cards and school advertisements inserted on special agreement.<lb/>  Nothing inserted for less <sic>shan</sic> <hi rend="italics">One</hi> Dollar.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Obituaries&#44; resolutions&#44; and complimentary notice of any kind&#44; 30 cents<lb/> per line&#59; marriage notices &#36;1 each.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">The wide circulation of the <hi rend="italics">Occident</hi> among the Jews&#44; not only in this city<lb/> and country&#44; but also in foreign lands&#44; makes it an excellent vehicle for<lb/> advertisements intended to meet their eyes.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Liberal inducements will be offered to all who are willing to act as our<lb/> agents&#44; and to clubs.</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Address&#44; <persName role="author">MAYER SULZBERGER</persName>&#44; EDITOR</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)">29 <hi rend="italics"><placeName>South Sixth St.&#44; Philadelphia</placeName>.</hi></p>
